15 WHEREAS, except for Bureau of Land Management lands included in the Lee Metcalf Wilderness, no
16 Montana lands identified by the National Landscape Conservation System have been formally designated as
17 wilderness; and
18 WHEREAS, the U.S. Forest Service has designated areas in Montana as inventoried roadless areas,
19 such as Garfield Mountain and Italian Peaks, adding more than 60,000 acres of defacto wilderness; and
20 WHEREAS, these Montana lands are in legal limbo, a situation that causes extensive federal litigation
21 as to what uses of the lands are appropriate and, in turn, places a burden on federal court resources; and
22 WHEREAS, uncertainty and wide swings in federal Executive Branch philosophy regarding the
23 administration of these lands are costing the public millions of dollars as forest assets burn and deteriorate and
24 as investments in forest road construction and improvements are being deliberately destroyed; and
25 WHEREAS, Montana's historic heritage, customs, and culture are linked to the proper stewardship and
26 use of the state's natural resources; and
27 WHEREAS, these lands are managed and treated as defacto wilderness in lieu of congressional action
28 to designate or release the lands, a situation that has resulted in a waste of forest assets, no management of
