1 public forests, and a harmful reduction in forest road construction and multiple-use access improvements; and
2 WHEREAS, the failure by Congress to release the lands designated for study by the Montana
3 Wilderness Study Act of 1977 and the National Landscape Conservation System or designated as roadless by
4 the Roadless Area Conservation Rule severely impedes Montana citizens from multiple uses of the lands,
5 thereby severely harming agriculture, timber harvesting, and other multiple-use interests, as well as Montana
6 communities and Montana families economically supported by those activities; and
7 WHEREAS, it is the consensus of the Montana Legislature that more than sufficient time has passed
8 for the study of these lands as to their suitability for preservation as wilderness; and
9 WHEREAS, national forest lands released from wilderness study or the roadless inventory would still
10 be subject to the National Forest Management Act, which requires extensive public involvement as the agency
11 develops and updates plans for the management and use of resources in each forest; and
12 WHEREAS, the Montana Legislature on behalf of the citizens of the state assert that the time is ripe for
13 final disposition of these lands.
14
15 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE AND THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF
16 THE STATE OF MONTANA:
17 That the Legislature supports scientific adaptive management to implement the multiple-use mandate
18 of public land use as mandated by the Multiple-Use Sustained-Yield Act of 1960 and the Federal Land Policy
19 and Management Act of 1976 to ensure the protection and improvement of public land health and to maintain
20 and improve the sustainability of federal lands, including forests, located in Montana.
21 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that the Legislature formally petitions Congress to enact legislation
22 releasing all wilderness study areas identified and specified in the Montana Wilderness Study Act of 1977 and
23 in the National Landscape Conservation System and all inventoried roadless areas identified by the Roadless
24 Area Conservation Rule in order to secure the rights of Montana citizens to use these public lands for public
25 purposes, including multiple uses, unless Congress confirms a study area for inclusion in the National
26 Wilderness Preservation System.
27 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that the Legislature petitions Congress to release all wilderness study
28 areas and inventoried roadless areas and implement the concept of multiple use in order to fulfill the federal
